# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cincinnati-reds-1876-1879
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1876 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] It was the team's first season of existence, having been formed as part of the brand new National League in 1876.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] This team was not related (except by name) to the previous Cincinnati Red Stockings National Association team, which had folded in 1870.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] One bright spot for the Reds was the play of Charley Jones, who led the club with a batting average of .286, had the second highest home run total in the league with four, and was among the league leaders in doubles and slugging percentage.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds played their first ever game on April 25, 1876, defeating the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Brown Stockings 2–1 at Avenue Grounds.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Wins would be few and far between for the Reds, as after putting up a solid 3–2 record in their opening five games, the Reds would go on an eleven-game losing streak to fall to 3–13.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] After defeating the Hartford Dark Blues 8–2 to end their losing streak, the Reds would then have a thirteen-game losing streak, and saw their record fall to 4–26.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] By the time the season was finished, Cincinnati had the worst record in the National League, as they ended the season with a 9–56 record, 42.5 games behind the first place Chicago White Stockings.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1877 Cincinnati Reds season** was the team's second season in the National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished sixth and last in the league with a record of 15–42, 25½ games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing dead last in the National League in the 1876 season, the Reds attempted to improve their club by signing Lip Pike, who spent the previous season with the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike was also named the manager of the team.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds got off to another terrible start, as they had a 3–11 start to the season, and Pike stepped down as the manager.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team was briefly disbanded by owner Josiah Keck, and although a group of eight businessmen stepped in to rescue the franchise, some Cincinnati players had been signed by other teams in the interim, and some newspapers subsequently refused to list the Red's results.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Bob Addy took over as player manager; however, he too saw very few wins as Cincinnati went 5–19 during his managerial stint.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Jack Manning then finished the year as player-manager, going 7–12, as the Reds had a 15–42 record and once again finished in the National League cellar, 25.5 games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another solid season for the Reds, hitting .310 with two homers and a team high 36 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Manning also had a solid year, hitting .317, as he had a team high 80 hits while tying Jones with a team high 36 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike hit .298 with a team high four home runs, and added 23 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, rookie Bobby Mitchell came up late in the season and was very impressive, leading Cincinnati with six victories and a team best 3.51 ERA in twelve games.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1878 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished second in the National League with a record of 37–23, four games behind the Boston Red Caps.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing their first two seasons in the National League in last place, the Reds were hoping for some improvement in the 1878 season.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Cal McVey of the Chicago White Stockings to become the team's new third baseman, and new manager.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Catcher Deacon White of the Boston Red Caps signed with Cincinnati.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White led the National League with a .387 batting average, 103 hits, eleven triples, 49 RBI, and a .545 slugging percentage with the Red Caps in 1877.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White also led the National League with 60 RBI while playing for the White Stockings in 1876.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, 23-year-old Will White was signed by the Reds.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White appeared in three games with the Boston Red Caps in 1877, going 2–1 with a 3.00 ERA.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another very solid season with the Reds, as he had a .310 batting average, along with a team high three home runs and 39 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White saw his production slip, however, he still hit .314 with 29 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Player-manager McVey was solid with a .306 average and two home runs along with 28 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White had a spectacular season, going 30–21 with a 1.79 ERA in 468 innings pitched.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds opened the season with a six-game winning streak, and stayed hot in their first twenty games, going 15–5, and were sitting in first place in the National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati then went on a six-game losing streak, falling to 15–11, and out of first place.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds never reclaimed first place; however, they finished the season strong, including a nine-game winning streak late in the year, to finish in second place with a 37–23 record, five games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1879 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fifth in the National League with a record of 43–37, 14 games behind the Providence Grays.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds were hoping to build off a great 1878 season, in which the team finished in second place in the National League with a 37–23 record.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In the off-season, the Reds announced that catcher Deacon White would become the player-manager.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Ross Barnes to play shortstop.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Barnes had missed most of the 1877 season and all of the 1878 season after falling ill.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In his last full season in 1876, Barnes played with the Chicago White Stockings, and led the NL with a .429 batting average, 138 hits, 126 runs, 38 doubles, and fourteen triples.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] King Kelly had a very solid season, hitting .348 with two home runs and 47 RBI, while another youngster, twenty-year-old Buttercup Dickerson, hit .291 with two home runs and a team high 57 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Deacon White rebounded from a poor 1878 season by his standards, as he hit .330 with a homer and 52 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, Will White led the NL with 75 starts, as he had a 43–31 record with a 1.99 ERA in his league high 680 innings pitched.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati started off hot, as they opened the season with a five-game winning streak.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] However, the club lost seven of their next eight games to fall under .500.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati had a mediocre 9–9 record after eighteen games, and player-manager Deacon White turned over his managerial duties to Cal McVey, who had been the Reds' player-manager in 1878.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati lost the first five games under McVey, however, the team began to play better, and ended the season with a 43–37 record, fifth in the league, and fourteen games behind the first-place Grays.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1899 Cleveland Spiders season** was the team's 13th and final season in Major League Baseball (MLB), and their 11th season in the National League (NL).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders' team owners, the Robison family, also owned the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] To strengthen the Perfectos, they transferred the Spiders' best players to St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis before the season, leaving Cleveland with a severely depleted roster.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As the Spiders played abysmally and continued to lose that season, fans stopped attending their home games, and other teams refused to travel to Cleveland to play road games against the Spiders.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This resulted in the Spiders being forced to play most of their games on the road.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders finished in 12th place, last in the NL, with a record of 20–134 (.130).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This remains the worst single-season record for an MLB team in terms of both losses and of winning percentage (.130).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team allowed 1,252 runs while only scoring 529, a run differential of −723 for the season, the worst in MLB history.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Spiders pitchers hit 109 batters, setting an MLB single-season record that would stand for 123 years until the 2022 Cincinnati Reds hit 110 batters.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early 1899, the owners of the Spiders, brothers Frank and Stanley Robison, bought the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis Browns baseball club from Chris von der Ahe, renaming it the Perfectos.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] However, they continued to retain ownership of the Cleveland club, an obvious conflict of interest that was later prohibited by MLB.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Robisons decided that a good team in St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis would draw more fans, so they transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including future Hall of Famers Cy Young, Jesse Burkett, and Bobby Wallace, as well as manager Patsy Tebeau to St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Most of the players Cleveland received were non-entities.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Jack Clements (known to history as one of MLB's few left-handed throwing catchers) and Joe Quinn were at the end of successful careers, and player-manager Lave Cross was traded back to St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis after the Spiders got off to an 8–30 start.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They also transferred numerous home games to the road—including the original Opening Day game to St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, the Spiders did not play their first home game until May 1.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early April, the Spiders started training in Terre Haute, Indiana.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Because of the cold weather, the team had to practice inside a gymnasium.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] With a decimated roster, it was apparent almost from the start that the Spiders would make a wretched showing.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After a poor start on the road, the Spiders played a home-opening doubleheader on May 1 in front of 100 fans.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They split the two games, moving up to 11th place.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] However, they were back in last before long.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On June 2, the Spiders led the Brooklyn Superbas, 10–0, in the sixth inning, but they blew the lead and ended up losing, 11–10.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On June 11, the Spiders lost to the Cincinnati Reds, 10–1, behind Frank Bates' poor pitching.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] It was the Spiders' 11th straight loss on that road trip.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The following day, the Spiders returned home and lost to the Pittsburgh Pirates in front of 58 fans.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team kept losing games, and losses came more and more frequently as the season went on.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On August 16, with Bates pitching, the Spiders lost to the Superbas, 13–2.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This led to criticism from the *Cleveland Plain Dealer*.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On August 18, the first-place Superbas completed their sweep of the Spiders, outscoring them, 43–8, in four games.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders notched their 100th loss of the season on August 31, falling to the Superbas, 9–3.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Two days later, the Spiders played a local amateur team in Johnstown, Pennsylvania, and lost, 7–5.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On September 12, the Spiders lost both games of a doubleheader to the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] At that point, they were 19–114 and had broken the MLB single-season record for losses, which had been 113.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On October 15, the Spiders ended their season by losing both games of a doubleheader to the Cincinnati Reds, by scores of 16–1 and 19–3.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders finished in 12th place, last in the NL.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After losing 40 of their last 41 games, they had a record of 20–134 (.130).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Their record is still the worst in Major League Baseball history.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They trailed the pennant-winning Brooklyn Superbas by 84 games, and finished 35 games behind the 11th place Washington Senators.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] For comparison, this would project to 21–141 under the current schedule, and Pythagorean expectation based on the Spiders' results and the current 162-game schedule would translate to a record of 25–137.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team's longest winning streak of the season was two games, which they accomplished once: on May 20 against the Phillies and May 21 against the Colonels.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They also accumulated the second-longest losing streak in league history, at 24 games from August 26 to September 16, trailing only the 26-game losing streak set by the 1889 Louisville Colonels.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders were winless against two teams: Brooklyn and Cincinnati.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Spiders opponents scored ten or more runs 49 times in 154 games.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Pitchers Jim Hughey (4–30) and Charlie Knepper (4–22) tied for the team lead in wins.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The pitching staff allowed a record 1,252 runs in 154 games.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders batters combined to hit 12 home runs, matching former Spiders star Bobby Wallace, who hit 12 home runs for St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The 1899 Spiders did lead the league in one statistic—games played.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Cleveland was the only team in the league to finish all of its games in the then-154 game schedule of the 1899 season, a rather unusual occurrence in that era.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Due to poor attendance, the Spiders played 112 road games, as a result of 35 of their planned home games being moved.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early 1899, team Robison Brothers publicly announced their intention to run the Spiders "as a sideshow", and fans took them at their word: after the first 16 home games, Cleveland's total attendance was 3,179, for a trifling average of 199 people per game.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, other NL teams refused to travel to Cleveland's League Park, since their cut of the ticket revenue would not even come close to covering their travel and hotel expenses.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, the Spiders only played 26 more home games for the rest of the season, including only eight after July 1.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Their records of 112 road games and 101 road losses will never be threatened: it is currently unbreakable under MLB's current scheduling practices, where a team plays a maximum of 81 road games.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The only time it was even considered approachable was the aforementioned 1994 Mariners, but the strike of that season ended the possibility of them breaking the record, and no team has played more than 81 road games since then (not counting 1 or 3 game tiebreaker playoff games).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] A mere 6,088 fans paid for Spiders home games in 1899, an average of 145 people per game.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis drew 373,909 fans for their home season, including 15,000 for one game (their home opener against the Spiders).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The dismal 1899 season was the end for the Spiders, and for National League baseball in Cleveland.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders were disbanded, along with the original Baltimore Orioles, the Louisville Colonels (Louisville, nor the entire state of Kentucky, has had another professional sports team since), and the original Washington Senators, as the National League contracted from 12 teams to 8.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The departure of baseball from Cleveland left an opening for the upstart American League, which opened for business in 1901 as a second major league and included among its charter members a new team, the Cleveland Blues.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Blues still exist today as the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Currently, the 2024 Chicago White Sox (121) has the post-1900 AL and MLB records for most losses in a season.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After the Spiders folded, a National League team would not play in Cleveland again until the Brooklyn Robins visited the then-Cleveland Indians in the 1920 World Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis, the Perfectos were renamed the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis Cardinals in 1900, which they are still called today.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Robisons purchasing of the Browns/Perfectos/Cardinals essentially began a turnaround for the organization, as they eventually became one of the most recognizable teams in baseball in the 20th century, appearing in 15 World Series and winning 9.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The **American Association of Base Ball Clubs** (**AA**) was a professional baseball league that existed for 10 seasons from 1882 to 1891.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Together with the National League (NL), founded in 1876, the AA participated in an early version of the World Series seven times versus the champion of the NL in an interleague championship playoff tournament.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] At the end of its run, several AA franchises joined the NL.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] After 1891, the NL existed alone, with each season's champions being awarded the Temple Cup (1894–1897).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] During its existence, the AA was often simply referred to as "the Association" in the media, in contrast to the NL, which was sometimes called "the League".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] It was also sometimes called the "Beer and Whiskey League".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The American Association (AA) distinguished itself in several ways from what it considered to be the puritanical National League (NL).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The new league established teams in what the NL leaders pejoratively called "river cities", including Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Louisville and St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Louis, with the inherent implication of lower morality or social standards in those cities.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] In contrast to the NL, the AA offered cheaper ticket prices, Sunday games and alcoholic beverages to its patrons.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] On November 8, 1881, at the Gibson House in Cincinnati, it was decided that individual teams in the league-to-be would operate their own affairs and set their own admission prices, under an agreement called the "guarantee system".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The NL at that time prohibited the sale of alcohol on its grounds, while the AA had no such restrictions, especially as several of its teams were backed by breweries and distilleries.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The AA became known as "The Beer and Whiskey League", another pejorative term applied by NL owners, which did not seem to bother the fans of the Association's clubs.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Beginning in 1884 and continuing through 1890, the champion of the AA met the champion of the NL in an early version of the World Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] These early Series were less organized than the modern version, with as few as three games played and as many as fifteen, and the contests of 1885 and 1890 ending in disputed ties.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The NL won four of these Series, while the AA won only one, in 1886 when the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Louis Cardinals) defeated the Chicago White Stockings (now the Chicago Cubs).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Over its lifetime, the AA was weakened by several factors.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] One was the tendency of some of its teams to jump to the NL.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The consistently stronger NL was in better position to survive adverse conditions.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Some owners of AA teams also owned a NL team.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The most significant blow to the AA was dealt by the Players' League, a third major league formed in 1890, which siphoned off talent and gate receipts.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] In a rare historical oddity, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (now the Los Angeles Dodgers) won the league's championship and represented the AA in the 1889 World Series, switched to the NL during the off-season, and then repeated the same feat.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] No player who spent the majority of his career in the AA is in the baseball Hall of Fame, although Bid McPhee of the Cincinnati Reds played eight of his eighteen seasons in the AA before the Reds moved to the National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The living legacy of the old Association is the group of teams that came over to the National League to stay.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The Pirates moved to the NL after the 1886 season, the Bridegrooms/Dodgers and the Cincinnati Reds after the 1889 season, and the Browns/Cardinals after the American Association folded following the 1891 season.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Following the reorganization and contraction of the NL from 12 teams down to 8 in 1900, half of the eight surviving teams were former members of the AA.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Several of the AA's home-field venues survived into the 1960s: The ballpark used by the 1891 Washington club evolved into Griffith Stadium; the home of the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Louis Browns, Sportsman's Park; and the city block occupied by the Reds, which evolved into Crosley Field.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Other than the clubs themselves, Crosley Field was the last physical remnant of the AA—it was the home field of the Cincinnati Reds until mid-season 1970 and was razed in April 1972.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] During the AA's existence, four clubs defected over to the NL: Allegheny City (joined NL 1887, later became the Pittsburgh Pirates), the Cleveland Spiders (joined NL 1889), the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (joined NL 1890, eventually renamed the Dodgers), and the Cincinnati Reds (joined NL 1890).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] At the AA's demise in 1891, four additional clubs joined the NL: the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Louis Browns (later the Cardinals), the Louisville Colonels, the Washington Statesmen (renamed the Senators), and the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] Therefore, from 1892 to 1899, when the NL consisted of 12 teams, 8 of them had been former AA clubs.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] All four have posted more than 10,000 all-time major-league victories.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] AA statistics are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB), the AA being one of six leagues deemed "major" by the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball in 1969.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The first line is the formation of the American Association (AA) in 1882, and the second marks the end of the American Association.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] World's Championship Series championships are shown with a "•", American Association Pennants in non-World Championship Series seasons are shown with a "#", and American Association Pennant winners who tied or lost the World Championship Series are shown with a "^".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] For the 1891 season, the Philadelphia Athletics were replaced by the Philadelphia Quakers of the Player's League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] The 1891 Cincinnati Kelly's Killers folded during the season and were replaced by the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-association-1882-1891] All non-American Association labels not labeled "NL" (National League) or "PL" (Players' League) are minor league teams.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] The **American League Central** is one of Major League Baseball's six divisions.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] This division was formed in the realignment of 1994 by moving three teams from the American League West and two teams from the American League East.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] Its teams are all located in the Midwestern United States.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] Along with the National League East, the AL Central is one of two divisions in the Major Leagues in which all of its members have won a World Series title.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] In fact, each team has captured at least two World Series championships.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] The Kansas City Royals were the most recent team from the division to win the World Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] The Cleveland Guardians were known as the Cleveland Indians until November 2021.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] The Chicago White Sox and Kansas City Royals are the only teams from the AL Central division to have won the World Series since the league realignment in 1994.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] In 1994, the Cleveland Indians were sitting atop the wild-card standings and would have qualified for the postseason as the AL's first wild card but on August 12 of that year, the season came to an early end due to a players strike, cancelling the remainder of the regular season and postseason.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] The 2006 Detroit Tigers were the first team from the Central to qualify as the wild card.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] MLB revamped the postseason starting in 2012, creating a new single-game playoff where two wildcards competed against each other while the division winners each received a bye.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] The winner of the American League wild card game moved on to face the top-seeded team of the AL in the American League Division Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] In 2013, the Indians became the first team from the AL Central to qualify as a wild card under the new postseason format.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] In 2014, the Kansas City Royals ended a 29-year postseason drought returning to the playoffs for the first time since winning the World Series in 1985.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] In 2020 only, eight teams, including the three division winners, played in a best-of-three Wild Card Series, with the winners advancing to the Division Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] Starting in 2022, the Wild Card field was increased to three teams, and along with the lowest-ranked division winner, qualified for the best-of-three Wild Card Series to determine the remaining two slots in the Division Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] † – Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the season was shortened to 60 games.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] The White Sox were tied with the Cleveland Indians but lost the runner-up honors due to an inferior head-to-head record (White Sox lost the season series 2–8 to the Indians).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] (**) The Tigers and Royals were tied for the 2nd Wild Card spot, but the Royals earned the tiebreaker by virtue of winning the regular season series 7–6.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] (***) Finished with the same record as the Houston Astros, but won the third wild-card spot due to the Tigers winning the season series 4–2.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/american-league-central] Totals updated through conclusion of the 2024 postseason.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] The **Cincinnati Reds**, also known as the **Cincinnati Red Stockings**, were a professional baseball team based in Cincinnati, Ohio that played from 1876–1879.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] The club predated the National League of which it became a charter member.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] John Joyce, who was an organizer of the Red Stockings club dismantled in 1870, reformed the club through a new company in 1875.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Two players from the 1870 season returned as part of a new professional nine which played local amateur clubs.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Joyce then sold the Reds to wealthy Cincinnati meat packer Josiah "Si" Keck during the winter.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] When the National League was formed on February 2, 1876 at the Grand Central Hotel in New York City, eight cities were selected to compete in the new major league: St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Louis, Hartford, Louisville, New York, Philadelphia, Chicago, Boston and Keck's Cincinnati club.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] They were managed by player/manager Charlie Gould, and outfielder Charley Jones led the Cincinnati offense with 4 home runs and 38 runs batted in.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] The 1876 team finished a dismal 9–56, last in the new eight-team National League; its winning percentage was the lowest in major-league history until the 1899 Cleveland Spiders surpassed it with a 20-134 record (.130).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] In 1877, helmed by the managing trio of Lip Pike, Bob Addy, and Jack Manning, the Reds finished 6th in the National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Pike, the second baseman, led the team with 4 home runs and rookie pitcher Bobby Mitchell led the team with 41 strikeouts.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] In the 1878 season, player/manager Cal McVey piloted Cincinnati to second place in the league.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Charley Jones led the team with 3 homers and Will White led the team with 169 strikeouts.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Sharing the managing duties, catcher Deacon White and McVey managed the team to 5th place.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Starting pitcher Will White hurled 232 strikeouts.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Baseball Hall of Fame member King Kelly played on the 1878 and '79 Reds.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Following the 1879 season, the club was disbanded.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] Justus Thorner, owner of the semi-professional Cincinnati Stars, purchased a new National League franchise and moved his club into the vacant spot left by the Reds; the Stars folded after the 1880 season.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879] A new Reds franchise debuted in 1882 in the American Association, and joined the National League in 1890.
